<TEXT>
the homeless the environment and other 
nonprofit causes could raise some 70 million a year if the united 
states allowed sale of postage stamps that carry the mail a message 
and a higher price according to a report released thursday 
the postagestamp suggestion was one of five proposals in a study 
of ways nonprofit organizations could find new ways to raise money 
as government aid shrinks and private donations level off the five 
suggestions could raise as much as 6 billion the report said 
the surcharge on the postage stamps would be given to the 
selected organizations sponsoring the stamps once the cost of 
printing and distribution had been deducted the report said 
for example a 25cent stamp dedicated to the homeless might 
actually sell for 35 cents with most of the extra dime going to 
homeless causes 
the study was conducted by the institute for public policy and 
administration of the union for experimenting colleges and 
universities 
these ideas should not be considered a substitution for 
traditional sources of revenue wrote mark rosenman director of 
the institute in particular government and charitable support 
must increase for nonprofit organizations to thrive 
however rosenman said federal programs providing money for 
nonprofit organizations have had 70 billion in funding cuts from 
1980 to 1986 
the causerelated postage stamps are used in several european 
countries and canada used a similar system for two years for raise 
money for the 1976 olympics the report said west germany raised 
some 20 million in 1986 on sales of stamps supporting youth causes 
the us postal service already allows commercial advertising in 
conjunction with the sale of stamps in an effort to maximize its own 
operating revenue in those cases the advertiser pays the postal 
service a fee in return for being allowed to place its message on 
stamp booklets sold at supermarkets and other outlets 
the other proposals included setting up special taxing districts 
that could raise up to 1 billion annually changing tax laws to 
encourage businesses to donate goods money or technical help using 
bond reserves the funds set aside to insure against potential 
losses to finance community development setting up special 
districts to levy taxes for specific purposes establishing 
statewide associations to negotiate discounts for group buying 
in all the institute considered some three dozen suggestions for 
new ways nonprofit organizations can raise money some of those 
included using credit cards to make monthly payments on pledges to 
nonprofit organizations providing a checkoff on income tax forms 
allowing taxpayers to designate a set amount for a specific purpose 
having the organizations charge for their services and setting up a 
nonprofit news service to cover important events and activities 
which might not otherwise be covered by the commercial press 
services 
</TEXT>
