<TEXT>
hundreds of thousands of people converged 
on the sacred lake of pushkar this week as they do every november 
when the full moon heralds the coming of winter to buy and sell 
camels and celebrate the renewal of life 
the rigors of their desert life are pushed aside for a week as 
they watch the dances of gypsy women and listen to ballads sung by 
transvestite performers 
most of the day is spent feeding grooming and haggling over 
prices of onehump camels but the hindu faithful make their way to 
the lake to bathe in the waters which tradition says spouted from 
the desert when lord brahman dropped a lotus from his hand 
married women unwrap their saris to bare their breasts and dip 
them in the lake believing this will cause them to give birth to 
more sons maimed beggars make their way to the lake seeking alms 
food and spiritual salvation 
the rituals peaked with the appearance of the full moon 
wednesday the 11th day of the hindu month of kartik and the day 
hindu traditions say lord brahma dropped his lotus brahma foremost 
in the hindu trinity of gods is reverered as the creator of the 
universe 
pushkar with a population of about 9000 holds more than 400 
temples where longtailed gray monkeys with black faces swing from 
dome to dome 
about 300000 villagers most from pushkars rajasthan state and 
more than 50000 camels and cattle have gathered for the annual 
festival 
about 7000 foreign tourists mostly from north america and 
western europe joined the celebration this year according to 
rvs bhanwar general manager of the rajasthan tourist company 
a city of colorful striped tents has sprung up to house the more 
affluent visitors who pay about 50 a night for an individual tent 
and meals 
for the foreigners the biggest attractions are the chances to 
ride camels and elephants and to watch the camel races 
but livestock sales along with the religious experience are the 
chief draws for indian participants 
the drought that had ravaged the desert state of rajasthan eased 
this year when the monsoon arrived after a threeyear absence this 
meant the livestock sellers were more interested in getting good 
prices instead of getting rid of beasts they could not afford to 
feed 
a strong camel is fetching as much as 135 to 200 this year 
