have kasper said wednesday we cannot do elective surgery we 
have to restrict the amount patients take home 
hemophiliacs depend on injections of concentrate because their 
bodies lack the ability to produce clotting substances putting them 
at constant risk of severe internal bleeding from everyday 
activities 
the american red cross which usually provides 20 percent of the 
nations supply of concentrate was ordered to keep its concentrate 
on the shelf because of a slight chance the product harbors the 
hepatitis or aids viruses 
an fda audit found that in a few instances the blood banks had 
not followed regulations for screening blood from which concentrate 
is made 
despite the order federal and red cross officials agree that it 
is highly unlikely that the concentrate is tainted the concentrate 
has already been treated to destroy any viruses that might have 
slipped through the screening 
my feeling is the products they are preparing are likely to be 
perfectly safe said dr joel solomon director of blood products 
for the fda 
