<TEXT>
opec oil ministers struck a tentative 
agreement thursday to curtail their soaring production and lift 
crude prices if adopted the pact would mean higher prices for 
gasoline and other petroleum products 
oil minister gholamreza aghazadeh of iran said he would return to 
tehran on friday to consult with his government before accepting the 
plan he said he might return to the opec meeting on sunday 
the arrangement he said would set total opec production at 185 
million barrels a day for the first six months of 1989 it would 
maintain the cartels benchmark price of 18 a barrel 
recent production increases have driven oil prices well below 
that mark 
cartel members often have ignored their quotas and analysts say 
current production has well exceeded 20 million barrels a day 
each dollar increase in the price of crude oil theoretically 
means a rise of 25 cents a gallon in retail gasoline prices 
a minister involved in the discussions with iran asked if the 
plan could be modified replied not from our point of view he 
spoke on condition of anonymity 
venezuelan oil minister julio cesar gil said its a fluid 
situation it depends mr aghazadeh is going to tehran for 
consultations 
the tentative plan worked out by the 13nation organization of 
petroleum exporting countries was put forth to break a deadlock 
between iran and iraq over a new output accord 
issam abdul raheem alchalabi iraqs oil minister has been 
insisting that iraqs production ceiling in any new pact be the same 
as irans aghazadeh had said no 
it was unclear exactly how that dispute was resolved 
asked if was still refusing to allow iraq to have the same quota 
as iran aghazadeh replied this is exactly the issue which i have 
to consult with my government 
aghazadeh who spoke to reporters after a late evening meeting 
with other ministers said iran would retain its share of total 
cartel output at 1427 percent 
i received a new proposal he said in which my main 
concern which is to preserve my percentage share is taken into 
consideration 
a ceiling of 185 million barrels would give iran a quota of 264 
million barrels a day it currently has a ceiling of 24 million 
barrels 
iraqs quota in the current accord is 15 million barrels a day 
iran has been allowed more to serve its larger domestic oil market 
aghazadeh said the other 11 members have agreed to give part of 
their share to iraq in an effort to break the deadlock 
the plan must be approved by all 13 opec ministers 
formal negotiations among the opec ministers had broken off 
shortly after the winter meeting began here monday 
the ministers had been scheduled to return to the bargaining 
table on wednesday but postponed their formal meeting until 
thursday then put it off until friday 
opec president rilwanu lukman who is nigerias oil chief and 
