westinghouse the new operator of the savannah 
river nuclear weapons plant will have projected expenses of 67 
billion under a 5year department of energy contract signed this 
week but could earn as much as 17 million per year doe officials 
say 
westinghouse savannah river co will operate the plant for the 
doe beginning april 1 replacing the du pont co which has managed 
srp since it was built in the early 1950s 
the plants nuclear reactors have been shut down because of 
safety concerns one reactor tentatively is scheduled to be 
restarted dec 31 but doe officials have said they may push that 
date back 
srp is the nations sole producer of plutonium and tritium which 
are used in the warheads of nuclear weapons 
the contract signed monday by paul w kaspar manager of the 
does savannah river operations and james s moore president of 
westinghouse river co covers a projected 67 billion over the 
5year period 
the contract allows westinghouse to be reimbursed for all 
allowable expenses and guarantees a base fee of 125 million 
during the first six months 
westinghouse also can earn up to 75 million in an award 
fee based on its performance during the first six months award 
fees will be handed out every six months the exact amount will be 
negotiated 
based on excellent performance wsrc could earn 13 million 
to 17 million per year in award fees the doe said 
the does savannah river operations meanwhile has requested 11 
million to build an engineering services office complex at srp the 
proposal which be approved by congress and doe officials in 
washington 
james m gaver a spokesman for the does savannah river 
operations said the doe office complex would be occupied primarily 
by bechtel savannah river co westinghouses lead engineering 
subcontractor gaver said the office complex could save the agency 
as much as 2 million a year in business costs 
