<DOCNO> AP881124-0168 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when the opec oil ministers come to town 
a small part of vienna is nearly turned into a middle eastern souk 
where the trading is in information rather than oriental rugs or 
brass plates 
a vast array of people appear when the ministers of the 13nation 
organization of petroleum exporting countries gather for their 
meetings 
the lobby of one of viennas luxury hotels is packed with 
reporters oil industry analysts and traders company officials 
us state legislators and assorted others 
it has all the hustle bustle pushing shoving shouting and 
dealing that characterizes any market 
any remark made by a minister is seized upon rumors abound and 
are spread quickly in small groups behind hotel pillars or on the 
lobby telephones 
reporters trip over oil traders in the pursuit of the latest 
scrap of news 
the right word can send the financial markets soaring millions 
of dollars can be made or lost 
unlike summits of other influential government officials opec 
meetings are openended briefings are scarce and press releases 
nonexistent 
the focus of attention is on the comingsandgoings of the 
ministers they stay in three nearby hotels overlooking the citys 
stadtpark a large garden with a statue of composer johann strauss 
most ministers are in one hotel bitter rivals iran and iraq are 
in separate hotels 
the ministers carry out most of their business by shuttling among 
the hotels their formal talks are held at opec headquarters about a 
mile away 
at this meeting they are trying to reach agreement on a new 
production accord that would limit their output and lift sagging oil 
prices 
as the ministers surrounded by bodyguards and aides hurry out 
of and into hotel elevators they are bombarded with questions 
some are more willing to talk than others and hold mininews 
conferences that generally last until the next elevator arrives 
irans oil minister gholamreza aghazadeh a former newspaper 
editor is more tolerant 
he and iraqi oil chief issam abdul raheem alchalabi are 
feuding over how much oil each will be allowed to produce in any new 
agreement 
their remarks are highly prized 
aghazadeh on tuesday sounded an optimistic note on the outcome of 
the meeting 
his brief statement i think we can reach an agreement 
sent oil prices soaring 
aghazadeh who gives the impression of a humble man later 
remarked ruefully i get the feeling that probably some traders 
benefited a lot by the reported remarks 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aghazadeh seems to prefer to have an aide translate his remarks 
into english when a large group gathers 
he sometimes speaks in english to add to the translation 
occasionally leading to confusion over his meaning 
one day he was asked if he were seeking both a higher opec quota 
and a higher percentage of the total output 
he said he couldnt change his percentage share but listening to 
the words on a tape recorder the translator could barely be heard 
saying probably im asking for both 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aghazadehs rival alchalabi is less willing to talk 
in fact he slips in and out of side doors to avoid reporters so 
the movements of his security personnel some of whom wait in the 
lobby are closely watched 
one man is easy to spot he has a shock of white in the front of 
his dark hair 
when he hasnt been seen for some time its likely his boss is 
gone 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
saudi arabias minister hisham nazer is the object of intense 
scrutiny 
observers like to say that each opec country has a single vote 
but saudi arabia has the barrels a reference to its enormous oil 
capacity and influence in the organization 
nazer says little and sometimes seems exasperated by the 
attention 
one day he returned to the hotel after a lunch with other 
ministers briefly went upstairs and then returned to the lobby 
noticing a few reporters starting to move toward him he remarked 
he hadnt been gone long enough to do anything 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
subroto the cheery former indonesian oil minister who is now 
secretarygeneral of opec seems to enjoy the activity 
one day an elevator door opened and out stepped subroto no 
reporters gathered 
he stopped did a small tap dance and waved his arms the hordes 
quickly surrounded him 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
libyas oil chief fawzi shakshuki met with mana saeed otaiba of 
the united arab emirates 
afterward shakshuki summed up their talks we discussed our 
problems 
after a few seconds of silence a reporter desperate for 
information asked what are your problems 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ecuadors energy minister diego tamariz is new and many dont 
yet immediately recognize him 
but a member of his security detail stands out he wears a 
borsalino hat with part of the brim snapped stylishly down an 
earring in one ear and his coat continently draped over his 
shoulders movie starstyle 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
prince abdul aziz bin salman of saudi arabia a man with a keen 
public relations sense invited a group of reporters for coffee in 
the wee hours of the morning 
the young prince a member of the royal family acted the 
gracious host making sure his guests were enjoying themselves 
analysts who have watched the prince at recent opec meetings 
say he is obviously being groomed to be a mover and shaker in the 
oil world 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
one of the few predictable things at the meeting is the departure 
and arrival of qatars minister abdul aziz bin khalifa al thani 
from the formal cartel talks 
the minister has an uncanny knack for arriving after everyone and 
leaving before anyone else 
longtime opec watchers have given him the nickname of lifo 
last in first out 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

