<TEXT>
chinese banks caught short of cash because of 
excessive lending and falling deposits have had to issue ious to 
farmers selling grain contracted by the state officials said 
thursday 
agriculture ministry official sun xiaoping said the cash 
shortfall has occurred in several areas of the country and is 
creating problems for farmers needing money to buy materials 
he said the livelihoods of some farmers could be affected if they 
are not paid soon for their grain crops 
but chen qizhen an official from the commerce ministry said the 
use of ious was not widespread and that farmers receiving the 
promissory notes were being paid within days 
the official china daily reported earlier this month that branch 
managers of the agriculture bank of china had met in beijing to 
discuss how to come up with about 51 billion needed to pay farmers 
over the next two months 
the report said the bank would have to attract large amounts of 
deposits during the rest of the year to support its farm product 
purchases 
the cash shortage it said was caused by unchecked lending in 
the first half of the year spiralling inflation and a 21 billion 
decline in the increase of new deposits over the first 10 months of 
the year 
