<TEXT>
broadcast ministers moved closer 
thursday to an agreement regulating western europes television 
programs 
ministers from the council of europe countries agreed on a 
proposal for the first continental program guidelines which would 
ban pornography racism and cigarette ads and limit advertising to 
15 percent of daily transmission time 
but a specific quota on how much programming must be 
europeanproduced a system suggested by france to stem the flood 
of american reruns was left out of the draft sent to the 22nation 
council for approval said meeting chairman bengt goransson 
at a twoday conference the ministers agreed that a high 
percentage of programming should be produced by europeans said 
goransson the swedish broadcast minster britain west germany 
holland and others opposed the quota idea 
we face today a situation in the television market where the 
european market is open for secondhand us production said 
goransson he told reporters that a set percentage could be a next 
step 
the spread of cable and satellite broadcasting has brought 
western stars cisco and pancho the monkees mr ed and other 
wellworn us series into homes all over western europe 
it isnt necessary that films always come from the states to 
europe said goransson but they should also come from europe 
to the states 
a meeting report estimated that less than 10 percent of the shows 
produced in europe ever leave the continent 
the draft convention also limits program interruptions for 
advertising says that ads cannot be directed at a single country 
and allows for suspension of programs that do not comply with some 
of the rules 
goransson said the proposal could be adopted by the council early 
next year although the leadership could still decide to make 
changes 
i think the united states will not be unhappy about the 
draft goransson said 
</TEXT>
